<p>The last thing I’ve got to work out is how to set the initial position of the falcon at power on. Previously, we would read the CANcoder angle, divide this by 360, multiple the answer by the number of encoder counts required to rotate the swerve module through one revolution, then call<br>
<code>    m_motor.SetSelectedSensorPosition(PowerOnPostionCount);</code></p>
<p>I have no idea how this is done now. Is it done in decimals of a rotation? Is it done relative to the mechanism rotations or relative to motor rotations?</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>TalonFX and CANcoder are both in units of rotations now. The Phoenix 6 equivalent to <code>SetSelectedSensorPosition</code> is <code>SetPosition</code>. Additionally, Phoenix 6 supports waiting for a new status signal to arrive using <code>WaitForUpdate</code>, which can be done at startup to make sure you have a valid CANcoder position for the <code>SetPosition</code> call.</p>
<p>Initializing the TalonFX to the CANcoder position would then be:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="cpp"><code class="lang-cpp">// wait for at most 250 ms for a CANcoder position, then set TalonFX position to match
motor.SetPosition(cancoder.GetPosition().WaitForUpdate(250_ms).GetValue());
</code></pre>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":8,"updated_at":"2024-01-15T06:02:40.571Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":5,"reads":57,"readers_count":56,"score":41.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":450050,"topic_slug":"converting-c-swerve-code-from-phoenix-5-to-phoenix-6-not-pro","display_username":"Benjamin Hall","primary_group_name":"CTRE","flair_name":"CTRE","flair_url":"/uploads/default/original/3X/1/b/1bd2b430e1bb6427d1c6504ff6abcd31de851a6d.png","flair_bg_color":"","flair_color":"","flair_group_id":57,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48146,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics"},"post_url":"/t/converting-c-swerve-code-from-phoenix-5-to-phoenix-6-not-pro/450050/3","custom_user_title":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3284746,"name":"WarrenR","username":"warren.reynolds1","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/a8b319/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-01-15T07:28:42.011Z","cooked":"<p>Do I have to consider the 12.8 ratio between the CANCoder and the Falcon Rotor Position or is that all taken care of?</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":8,"updated_at":"2024-01-15T07:28:42.011Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":50,"readers_count":49,"score":15.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":450050,"topic_slug":"converting-c-swerve